## ANTLR: Overview

.background images/cool.png

- ANTLR is a well known parser generator 
- It can generate parsers for many programming languages
- It has a big and vibrant community


## ANTLR: DSL Example

.code ./code/bench/antlrp/JSON.g4 /^grammar/,/1 OMIT$/

: NEXT: What should the code look like?


## What The Code Should Look Like

.code ./code/bench/combp/json.go /1 OMIT$/,/2 OMIT$/
.code ./code/bench/combp/json.go /3 OMIT$/,/4 OMIT$/


## What The Generated Files  Really Look Like

- Generated Go files: json_base_listener.go, json_lexer.go, json_listener.go and json_parser.go
- To be fair: The listeners aren't always necessary.


## What The Code Really Looks Like

.code -edit ./code/bench/antlrp/json_parser.go /^func jsonParserInit/,/^}/


## How To Use The Generated Code

Call it like this:

.code ./code/bench/bench_test.go /1 OMIT$/,/2 OMIT$/

The result is:

.code ./code/bench/antlrp/json_parser.go /^type IJsonContext/,/^}/


## My ANTLR Conclusion

.background images/alarm.png

- A real programmer can write Java in any programming language.
- I got to find out how ANTLR and other parsers are recovering from errors.
- Unfortunately ANTLR is very different from a parser combinator.


## Error Handling: Reading Papers

.background images/doctors-degree.png

Look at paper: `~/work/ErrorRecoveryInPEG-Parsers.pdf`


## Next Attempt At Error Recovery

- Parser combinators are working with the call stack of the program.
- So individual parsers can't be called without this context.
- Go with the flow / call stack.

## We Need Different Modes

.background images/hard-work.png

<table>
<thead> <th>Mode</th> <th>Direction</th> <th>Description</th> </thead>
<tbody>
<tr> <th>happy</th> <td>forward</td> <td>normal parsing</td> </tr>
<tr class="hideable hidden"> <th>error</th> <td>backward</td> <td>after potential error: going back searching for an alternative way</td> </tr>
<tr class="hideable hidden"> <th>handle</th> <td>forward</td> <td>after confirming error: going forward to parser at error position</td> </tr>
<tr class="hideable hidden"> <th>happy</th> <td>forward</td> <td>after handling error: normal parsing</td> </tr>
<tr class="hideable hidden"> <th>rewind</th> <td>backward</td> <td>after normal parsing failed again: go back to handling error</td> </tr>
<tr class="hideable hidden"> <th>escape</th> <td>forward</td> <td>after all handling failed: move to some safe spot and parser</td> </tr>
</tbody>
</table>

## All Modes Have To Be Implemented For All Branch Parsers

.background images/sleepless.png

- MapN: Map a sequence of N successful parsers to some arbitrary output.
- SeperatedMN: Use a parser many times and an optional separator parser inbetween.
- Sequence: Apply a list of parsers (all producing the same kind of output) in sequence.
- FirstSuccessful: Try a list of parsers until one succeeds.
- Expression: Parse (mathematical) expressions.


## The Complexity Of Branch Parsers Exploded

.background images/crying.png

- Back to the drawing board.
- What is it really that makes error recovery possible?


## The Solution For Error Recovery

.background images/enlighten.png

- It must be possible to call a parser directly.
- Branch parsers must be able to run after some child parser.
- So all parsers need an ID.
- Use parser with least waste for recovery.
- All parsers are kept in a slice of parsers by the orchestrator.
- Need to remember the parent parser.
- Parent parsers can be dynamic:
- Parsers used in multiple places.
- Expressions with parentheses.


## The Last Tough Decision For Parsing Expressions

<table>
<thead><tr> <th>Topics</th> <th>1 subparser</th> <th>N subparsers</th> </tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr> <th>children</th> <td>trivial</td> <td>lots of parsers but doable; prentheses???</td> </tr>
<tr class="hideable hidden"> <th># of children</th> <td>always 3</td> <td>N * M + 2 + parentheses</td> </tr>
<tr class="hideable hidden"> <th>who failed?</th> <td>remember err + op</td> <td>trivial: ID</td> </tr>
<tr class="hideable hidden"> <th>who recovered?</th> <td>remember err + op</td> <td>done automatically</td> </tr>
<tr class="hideable hidden"> <th>parents?</th> <td>remember err + ops + levels</td> <td>remember in result</td> </tr>
<tr class="hideable hidden"> <th>parsers</th> <td>just 2 to the outside</td> <td>facade parsers for ops + parentheses</td> </tr>
</tbody>
</table>


